      • callsTo

        public static <T> T callsTo(Class<T> clazz)
        Generates a proxy object for use with other FuncitoPlay2 static methods. This proxy should not be used for any other purposes. It is a convenience pass-thru to FuncitoDelegate.callsTo(Class). Example usages are: 

         
     // inlined:
     Function<MyClass,RetType1> func = functionFor( callsTo(MyClass.class).methodWithRetType1() );

     // or extracted for repeat usage
     final MyClass CALLS_TO = callsTo(MyClass.class);
     Function<MyClass,RetType1> func2 = functionFor( CALLS_TO.method1WithRetType1() );
     Function<MyClass,RetType2> func3 = functionFor( CALLS_TO.method2WithRetType2() );

        Stubs are cached, so this method can be called multiple times for the same class without penalty. But a single proxy can also be reused for creating multiple Play! Function objects.

        Parameters:
        clazz - is the class to be proxied
        Returns:
        a proxy which can be used by other FuncitoPlay2 static methods

      • functionFor

        public static <T,V> F.Function<T,V> functionFor(V proxiedMethodCall)
        Generates a Play! Framework Function object that wraps a method call or method chain. Resulting Function is as thread-safe as the method itself. Example usage is:

        Function<MyClass,RetType1> func = functionFor( callsTo(MyClass.class).methodWithRetType1() );

        You can wrap methods with parameters, so long as you statically provide values for each parameter. Provided parameter values are statically bound to the Function and may not be changed:

        Function<MyClass,RetType1> func = functionFor( callsTo(MyClass.class).methodWithArgs("abc", 123L) );
        // all invocations of func will use "abc" and 123L as the arguments to methodWithArgs

        It is also possible to wrap method call chains, with some restrictions:

        MyClass callsTo = callsTo(MyClass.class);
        Function<MyClass,RetType2> func = functionFor( callsTo.methodWithRetType1().methodWithRetType2() );

        Restrictions for chaining are that intermediate return types (all except for the final return type in the chain) must be proxyable by the current Proxy provider, just like the initial target type. In the above example this means MyClass and RetType1 must be proxyable, but RetType2 need not be proxyable. Intermediate return types also cannot be a Java Generic type because of type erasure.

        Parameters:
        proxiedMethodCall - is the return value from a method call to a FuncitoPlay2 proxy object
        Returns:
        a Play! 2 Function object that wraps the method call or chain.

      • callbackFor

        public static <T> F.Callback<T> callbackFor(Object proxiedMethodCall)
        Generates a Play! 2 Callback object that wraps a method call or method chain. Resulting Callback is as thread-safe as the method/chain itself. This Callback generator can only be used for method calls/chains with a non-void return type, even though the return type is ignored. For a Callback generator that works with void returning methods/chains, see voidCallback(). Example usage is:

        Callback<MyClass> cmd = callbackFor( callsTo(MyClass.class).methodWithNonVoidReturnType() );

        You can wrap methods with parameters, so long as you statically provide values for each parameter. Provided parameter values are statically bound to the Callback and may not be changed:

        Callback<MyClass> cmd = callbackFor( callsTo(MyClass.class).methodWithArgs("abc", 123L) );
        // all invocations of callback will use "abc" and 123L as the arguments to methodWithArgs

        It is also possible to wrap method call chains, with some restrictions:

        MyClass callMyClass = callsTo(MyClass.class);
        Callback<MyClass> cmd = callbackFor( callsMyClass.methodWithRetType1().methodWithRetType2() );

        Restrictions for chaining are that intermediate return types (all except for the final return type in the chain) must be proxyable by the current Proxy provider, just like the initial target type. In the above example this means MyClass and RetType1 must be proxyable, but RetType2 need not be proxyable. Intermediate return types also cannot be a Java Generic type because of type erasure.

        Type Parameters:
        T - is the input type of the Callback
        Parameters:
        proxiedMethodCall - is the return value from an inlined method call to a FuncitoFJ proxy object
        Returns:
        a Play! 2 Callback object that wraps a method call or chain.
        See Also:
        voidCallback()

      • prepareVoid

        public static <T> T prepareVoid(T t)
        Prepares a method-call or method-chain call that terminates with a void return type, for generation of a Play! 2 Callback object. Use of this method must be followed with execution of one of the void-Callback methods: voidCallback(), voidCallback(TypedMode), voidCallback(Mode). Resulting Callback is as thread-safe as the method/chain itself. Example usage is:

        prepareVoid(callsTo(MyClass.class)).methodWithVoidReturnType();

        You can wrap methods with parameters, so long as you statically provide values for each parameter. Provided parameter values are statically bound to the Callback and may not be changed:

        prepareVoid(callsTo(MyClass.class)).voidMethodWithArgs("abc", 123L);
        // all invocations of callback will use "abc" and 123L as the arguments to voidMethodWithArgs

        It is also possible to wrap method call chains, with some restrictions:

        MyClass callMyClass = callsTo(MyClass.class);
        prepareVoid(callsMyClass).methodWithRetType1().voidMethod();

        Restrictions for chaining are that intermediate return types (final return type does not matter because it is void) must be proxyable by the current Proxy provider, just like the initial target type. In the above example this means MyClass and RetType1 must be proxyable. Intermediate return types also cannot be a Java Generic type because of type erasure.

        Type Parameters:
        T - is the input type of the Callback being prepared
        Returns:
        the same Funcito proxy object that is passed in. Provided for fluent API so that desired method chain call may be directly appended.
        See Also:
        voidCallback()

      • voidCallback

        public static <T> F.Callback<T> voidCallback()
        Generates a Play! 2 Callback object that wraps a method call or method chain. Resulting Callback is as thread-safe as the method/chain itself. This Callback generator is only appropriate for method calls/chains with a void return type, and it requires previous usage of prepareVoid(Object). Example usage is:

        prepareVoid(callsTo(MyClass.class)).methodWithVoidReturnType();
        Callback<MyClass> cmd = voidCallback();

        Type Parameters:
        T - is the input type of the Callback
        Returns:
        a Play! 2 Callback object that wraps a previously prepared method call or chain.
        See Also:
        prepareVoid(Object)
